            "description": "The next generation lithography systems operate using EUV radiation at a wavelength of 13.5 nm. This EUV radiation creates a plasma in the low pressure background gas of the system. \nIt is important to get a physical insight on ions inside the EUV-induced plasma, as they can influence the lifetime of the system. \n\nThe goal of this study is to experimentally investigate Ion Energy Distribution Functions in EUV-induced plasmas. The amount of research conducted on these kind of plasmas is scarce and up to now, industry mostly relies on numerical simulations. Therefore, experimental investigation is of utmost importance. \n\nIn order to measure ion energy distributions, an Electrostatic Quadrupole Plasma analyzer (EQP) is used, which is a mass spectrometer containing an energy filter. \nThe EUV-induced plasma is created by photoionization by an EUV beam, produced by a pulsed xenon pinch discharge. \n\nBoth time averaged and time resolved measurements are performed succesfully in hydrogen and nitrogen plasmas, giving new insights in investigating the optics lifetime in next generation lithography tools. \nRating: 8/10 \n\n",
