            "description": "The goal of this study was to conduct experiments and investigate to what extent the data corresponds with a known scattering theorem.\n\nThis can be used to know if a simple model is convenient to describe scattering in media. If a\nsimple model is made which can describe the scattering behavior in a medium, it is often not\nnecessary to make use of complex models and experiments.\nIt is important to have knowledge about the scattering behavior in media, as it has a contribution\nin the intensity profiles. Intensity profiles are of great use making LED's or other light sources,\nbecause they play a major role in the brightness of a light source, or the fact that it emits soft\nor hard light.\n\nIn order to conduct the experiments, a CCD camera and an optical \ffiber are used to measure\nthe intensity profile of a laser beam. This laser beam is going through a medium where the\nincident light is partly scattered and where a small part is absorbed. The medium used in the\nexperiments is silicone with titanium dioxide (TiO2), which is the scattering material.\nThe mixture of silicone and TiO2 results in intensity profiles, which are compared with a simplified Mie model. Mie theory is the theory used in this study for describing scattering phenomena.\n\n",
